SIMPLE: hollow
RECORDS: 7

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hollow
<hw>Hol"low</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>holow</ets>,
<ets>holgh</ets>, <ets>holf</ets>, AS. <ets>holh</ets> a hollow, hole.
Cf. <er>Hole</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having an empty space or
cavity, natural or artificial, within a solid substance; not solid;
excavated in the interior; <as>as, a <ex>hollow</ex> tree; a
<ex>hollow</ex> sphere.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hollow</qex> with boards shalt thou make it.</q> <rj><qau>Ex.
xxvii. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Depressed; concave; gaunt; sunken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With <qex>hollow</qex> eye and wrinkled brow.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Reverberated from a cavity, or resembling such a
sound; deep; muffled; <as>as, a <ex>hollow</ex> roar</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not sincere or faithful; false; deceitful; not
sound; <as>as, a <ex>hollow</ex> heart; a <ex>hollow</ex>
friend.</as></def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hollow newel</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>an opening
in the center of a winding staircase in place of a newel post, the
stairs being supported by the wall; an open newel; also, the stringpiece
or rail winding around the well of such a staircase.</cd> --
<col><b>Hollow quoin</b></col> <fld>(Engin.)</fld>, <cd>a pier of stone
or brick made behind the lock gates of a canal, and containing a hollow
or recess to receive the ends of the gates.</cd> -- <col><b>Hollow
root</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Moschatel</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Hollow square</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Square</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Hollow ware</b></col>, <cd>hollow vessels; -- a trade name for
cast-iron kitchen utensils, earthenware, etc.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b>- Concave; sunken; low; vacant; empty; void; false;
faithless; deceitful; treacherous.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hollow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hollow
<hw>Hol"low</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A cavity,
natural or artificial; an unfilled space within anything; a hole, a
cavern; an excavation; as the <xex>hollow</xex> of the hand or of a
tree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A low spot surrounded by elevations; a depressed
part of a surface; a concavity; a channel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Forests grew⟦br⟧
Upon the barren <qex>hollows</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I hate the dreadful <qex>hollow</qex> behind the little wood.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hollow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hollow
<hw>Hol"low</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hollowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hollowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make hollow, as by digging,
cutting, or engraving; to excavate.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Trees rudely
<xex>hollowed</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hollow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hollow
<hw>Hol"low</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Wholly; completely; utterly; --
chiefly after the verb <xex>to beat</xex>, and often with
<xex>all</xex>; <as>as, this story beats the other all
<ex>hollow</ex></as>. See <er>All</er>, <pos>adv.</pos></def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The more civilized so-called Caucasian races have beaten the Turks
<qex>hollow</qex> in the struggle for existence.</q>
<rj><qau>Darwin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hollow</ent>⟦br⟧

